Here's how to handle saving/restoring draft text using MAUI's app lifecycle events and `Preferences`:

**In `App.xaml.cs`** — hook into lifecycle events:

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    public App()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        MainPage = new NavigationPage(new NotePage());
    }

    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    {
        var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

        window.Deactivated += (s, e) =>
        {
            if (MainPage is NavigationPage nav &&
                nav.CurrentPage is NotePage notePage)
            {
                notePage.SaveDraft();
            }
        };

        window.Activated += (s, e) =>
        {
            if (MainPage is NavigationPage nav &&
                nav.CurrentPage is NotePage notePage)
            {
                notePage.RestoreDraft();
            }
        };

        return window;
    }
}
```

**In `NotePage.xaml`:**

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="YourApp.NotePage"
             Title="Notes">
    <Editor x:Name="NoteEditor"
            Placeholder="Start typing your note..."
            VerticalOptions="FillAndExpand" />
</ContentPage>
```

**In `NotePage.xaml.cs`:**

```csharp
public partial class NotePage : ContentPage
{
    private const string DraftKey = "note_draft";

    public NotePage()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        RestoreDraft();
    }

    public void SaveDraft()
    {
        Preferences.Set(DraftKey, NoteEditor.Text ?? string.Empty);
    }

    public void RestoreDraft()
    {
        NoteEditor.Text = Preferences.Get(DraftKey, string.Empty);
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`Window.Deactivated`** fires when the app goes to the background — save here.
- **`Window.Activated`** fires when returning to the foreground — restore here.
- **`Preferences`** is a lightweight key-value store built into MAUI (backed by `SharedPreferences` on Android, `NSUserDefaults` on iOS).
- The draft is also restored in the constructor so it survives a full process kill.

For larger text, swap `Preferences` for `File.WriteAllTextAsync` to `FileSystem.AppDataDirectory` instead.
